      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Look, the plain summary is this: you want to limit your exposure while making sure you aren't unfairly taking on the agency's inherent business risks. When negotiating indemnification, try to narrow the scope so you are only indemnifying them for your *negligence* or *breach of contract*, not for their own business mishaps. You should aim to carve out exceptions for their own errors or the actions of third parties they hire.\n\nFor Limitation of Liability, you must negotiate a reasonable cap on your financial responsibility, ideally tied to the contract value itself (e.g., \"liability shall not exceed the total fees paid under this agreement\"). Never sign a clause that says you are responsible for *all* losses without defining the trigger event! Remember, if the clause is silent on negligence, it often defaults to the harshest possible interpretation, which is usually worse for you than a well-defined cap.\n\nIn short, challenge broad language! Don't let them make you the ultimate bailout fund for their entire operation. Keep your requests surgical, like a highly focused, non-messy goblin raid.\n\nThe trick is to distinguish between \"I messed up\" (which you should cover under indemnification, but maybe capped)",
